                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d379">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">760C.62/1144: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister Resident in Iraq</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Knabenshue</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Baghdad</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-08-29T13:00:00+03:00"
                            >August 29, 1939—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 29—9:34 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>46. The Minister for Foreign Affairs has just told me that “our position is
                    clear, we are an ally of England”.</p>
                <pb facs="0392" n="380" xml:id="pg_380"/>
                <p>The German Minister tells me that in the event of war [he?] is ready to depart at
                    a moment’s notice and will turn over interests to Iranian Legation believing
                    that the United States Government would be unwilling to accept charge of German
                    interests.</p>
                <p>The British air force have taken measures to protect the pipe line with their
                    local levies and armored car sections together with subsidized tribesmen.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Knabenshue</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
